        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName>, <date>May 25<hi rend="sup"
                        >th</hi> 5608</date></p>
            <p>Reverend Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have the honor, to send you hereby a small article<lb/> for your
                “Occident,” and after having read it you may<lb/> decide of its being worthy to be
                published. Believing,<lb/> as I do, you will agree with me, contending, that<lb/> a
                comparison of the present struggle with that<lb/> of <persName>Maimonides</persName>
                is not improper, I should think, it<lb/> will also appease some pious minds
                excited<lb/> by the present state of our eternal religion.<lb/> My English
                expression (style) will acquire many<lb/> corrections and you will have the kindness
                to do so.<lb/> I was taking care to express myself as distinctly<lb/> as possible,
                but a foreigner—as I am, only two<lb/> years in this country, it will require your
                issue.<lb/> To the blaming Article of “truth,” who amongst<lb/> other mistakes also
                pretends: “the <del>reading</del>
                <hi rend="underline">annual</hi><lb/> reading of the Pentateuch was already
                introduced<lb/> by <persName>Ezra the Scribe</persName>,” I furnish you the
                following<lb/> passage taken of <add>Hebrew</add>: <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> “some
                congregations use to read the Pentateuch but once<lb/> in three years.”—
                    <persName>R. Benjamin de Tudela</persName> says:<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add></p>
            <p>Do these passages not prove, that “<add>Hebrew</add>” is <add>Hebrew</add>?, that<lb/>
                <persName>Ezra the Scribe</persName> did not introduce the <hi rend="underline"
                    >annual<lb/> reading</hi></p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>reading of the Pentateuch, or else the <addressee>Hebrew</addressee><lb/> surely
                followed him and not read the P. but once<lb/> in three years.
                    <persName>Ezra</persName> did introduce, that they<lb/>
                <del>set</del> should read in the Pentateuch in generally, he<lb/> also ordered:
                    <add>Hebrew</add> of. Gemara<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add> f. 82. 1.; but to <del>read</del> finish the P. in one year<lb/>
                whence will <del>fr</del> “truth” prove, that <persName>Ezra</persName> has
                    order<add>ed</add><lb/> so? I can prove the contrary. The Gemara says<lb/> in
                    <add>Hebrew</add>: <add>Hebrew</add> “the <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> the Palestinian
                Jews read the Pentateuch but once<lb/> in three years.” Proves that not
                distinctly<lb/> against “truth”? No doubt, <hi rend="underline">many</hi> centuries
                    af<add>ter</add>]<lb/>
                <persName>Ezra</persName> in <placeName>Palestine</placeName> and other countries
                the P. was read but once in<lb/> three years and in
                    <placeName><sic>Babylonien</sic></placeName> the reading in<lb/> one year was
                instituted probably <hi rend="underline">700 or 800 year<add>s</add></hi><lb/>
                after. <persName>Ezra the Scribe</persName>. Please, Sir, make use of<lb/>
                <del>it</del> these remarks in your “Occident,” you may <add>?</add><lb/> upon my
                quotations, I <del>have</del> shall send you in<lb/> future contributions for your
                paper but now, Sir,<lb/> I stop, <add>Hebrew</add>—and besides that, I do not<lb/>
                know, how you are pleased with my com<add>m</add>encement<lb/> Most
                respectfully<lb/> Yours<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Dr Kohlmeyer</persName></p>
            <p>Rev. <addressee>I. Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
